ons of the Holocaust, Western modernity, consumerism, globalisation and the nature of sociology. The book shows how Eurocentrism, the neglect of issues of gender and a lack of awareness of the racism faced by Europe’s non-white ethnic minorities seriously limit Bauman’s analyses of Western societies. At the same time, it points to Bauman’s repeated insistence on the need for sociologists to take a moral stance in favour of the world’s poor and downtrodden as being his most valuable legacy. The book will be of great interest to sociologists. Its readability will be valued by undergraduates and postgraduates and it will attract a readership well beyond the discipline.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAntiSemitism.  aConsumerism.  aEmmanuel Levinas.  aEnlightenment.  aEurocentrism.  aGender.  aHolocaust.  aLegislators and Interpreters.  aLiquid Modernity.  aModernity.  aPostmodernism.  aPostmodernity.  aThe Holocaust.  aZygmunt Bauman.  acontemporary sociology.  aethics.  aliquid metaphor.  ametaphoricity.  amorality.  asocio-economic change.  asolid metaphor.  asolid modernity.1 aRattansi, Ali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610588240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526105882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526105882/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles